T1  - Los de Adentro, Los de Afuera: Transnational Cuba, "17-D," and the Cuban-American predicament
AN  - 1776460986
AB  - What started as a dinner table rallying cry became a dream deferred. By the late 1960s, the promise of a “next year in Cuba” had receded for most Cuban exiles into the realm of implausibility. The idea, however, retained a peculiar currency. According to critic Ricardo Ortiz, dominant strains of a burgeoning “Cuban-American” culture became prisoner to “a historical paradigm that both promise[d] return and stave[d] it off by virtue of [a] structural reliance on the indefinite deferral of that return.” Life for many, in other words – in Little Havana, Union City, or New York – revolved around an emotional captivity, an “idealized addiction to [a] redemptive promise” that most exiles in their heart of hearts increasingly knew would never materialize, not in the near future anyway (Ortiz 2007, 134–135). Today, in light of the restoration of diplomatic relations between Washington and Havana, the existential paralysis that once defined the Cuban-American community seems decidedly passé. Long ago it cracked at the seams. For though Miami’s grandest prophecies of anti-communist salvation fell short, since the late 1970s tens of thousands of Cuban émigrés and their descendants have gone back to the island to visit their relatives, albeit initially on short, expensive and controversial package tours. By the 1990s, what scholar Antonio López calls the “Cuban-American return narrative” had acquired the predictable familiarity of a literary trope. Memoir after memoir codified the defining characteristics of the archetypal “returnee”: white, descending from the pre-revolutionary middle and upper classes, liable to find an “Afro-Cuban-occupied” family home (López 2012, 185–212). Now, amidst a flurry of Cuba-related media coverage, fresh or newly replayed stories about “bridges to/from” the island offer human-interest analogues to the budding annals of US–Cuba rapprochement (Pedro Ruiz: Coming Home 2011; Bridges to/from Cuba 2015; Vincent 2015; Oye Cuba! A Journey Home (2015; in production)). A year after the shock of what Cubans have taken to calling “17-D” – 17 December 2014, the date Barack Obama and Raúl Castro first announced their negotiated breakthrough – feel-good tales of family reunions and diasporic collaborations seem to be setting the affective stage for the bigger embrace of US and Miami capital still to come.
